Type classes — the dominant pattern this enables.

A type class is a contract that says: any type a that has an instance of my-class-of-a available can do these operations. Instead of subtyping, where the type itself implements an interface, the capability is provided externally, by a separate value — the instance.

Three pieces define a type class. First, the trait — for example, a show trait with a show method that turns an a into a string. That is the contract. Second, the given instances — one for each type that should support the operation, such as a show for integer and a show for string. Third, a summoner — usually a generic method with a using parameter, often dressed up with an extension method for nicer syntax at the call site.

The win over plain subtyping is threefold. You can add capabilities to types you do not own — string and integer come from the standard library, yet you can write show instances for both. You can have multiple instances scoped differently — a person ordered by age in one module, by name in another. And the capability is decoupled from the type — a person is not a show, it simply has a show instance available nearby. Instances can even build on each other: a given show for a list of a, which itself requires a show for a, lets you show a list by showing each element. Then a generic describe method that takes a using show prints any value with an instance — an integer, a string, a list, even a nested list, where the list instance fires recursively. That composability is why type classes are the dominant abstraction pattern in modern Scala.
